library(readxl)
library(distributional)
get_my_data <- function(student_id) {
  set.seed(student_id)
  all_data <- readr::read_rds("https://bit.ly/monashretaildata")
  while(TRUE) {
    retail <- filter(all_data, `Series ID` == sample(`Series ID`, 1))
    if(!any(is.na(fill_gaps(retail)$Turnover))) return(retail)
  }
}

Q5

The two STL decompositions given have differences in trend and variation.

Chosen due to its smoother trend and smaller variation indicated by the grey boxes, the ideal decomposition is plotted over larger intervals with window = 311.

Seasonality remains a consistent feature in both decompositions when the season component has a value of 11 and 311. The variation of the plot with window = 311 is marginally smaller. This variation can be analysed using the remainder component.

The remainder shows peaks around 2010 and trough in 2020 which deviate from it fluctuating around 0. According to the ABS, real net disposable income grew by 6.3% during 2010-2011 which could be a reason for this spike (ABS, October 2011, Australian System of National Accounts, 2010-2011, [https://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Previousproducts/5204.0Main%20Features22010-11?opendocument&tabname=Summary&prodno=5204.0&issue=2010-11&num=&view=# ], ABS website, accessed 22nd March 2022). The trough in 2020 may be attributed to COVID19

Transformation and Differencing

Applying a log transformation to Turnover results in an additive pattern as referenced by the STL decomposition plotted above (line 89-91) and the time series plotted below (line 96-98). This satisfies one property of stationary data. However, there is no mean reverting behavior. A trend can be fitted to the time series generated by (line 96-98). This is fixed below by taking the first seasonal difference. Taking the first seasonal difference with lag=4 for monthly data as shown with line (line 99-102) results in mean centered around the origin.lag=4 is used because 4 is a multiple of 12 i.e the number of months. Taking lag=8 or lag=12 generates heteroscedasticity in the time plot in spite of generating mean reverting behavior.

retail |> gg_tsdisplay(log(Turnover),plot_type = "partial", lag=48)

retail |> gg_tsdisplay(box_cox(Turnover,lambda=-0.4),plot_type = "partial", lag=48)

retail |> gg_tsdisplay(difference(log(Turnover),12) |> difference(),
                       plot_type = "partial",lag=48)

Unit Root Test The KPSS unit root test is conducted. The null hypothesis states that the log transformation of Turnover with 1 seasonal difference is stationary. The test generates a p-value of 0.1. The decision rule and conclusion state that we fail to reject the null hypothesis at a 1%, 5%, and 10% significance level respectively.This indicates that no further transformations or differencing is necessary.

retail |> features(
  difference(log(Turnover),12) |> difference(),
  unitroot_kpss
)
